<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-083-806  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 083 806.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  March 6 1989 v6 n9 p13(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microsoft pledges wide PM-based printer support: hopes to loosenPostScript stronghold. (Presentation Manager)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bernard, Diane.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Microsoft Corp is moving aggressively to promote the use of thePresentation Manager graphical user interface within the printingenvironment.andP;  Microsoft plans to support the creation of devicedrivers for the Presentation Manager environment as well ashigh-end laser printers.andP;  Printer makers are encouraged to adoptMicrosoft's Graphical Programming Interface (GPI) for PresentationManager.andP;  One such printer is being developed by PhoenixTechnologies Ltd. Hewlett-Packard is also working on combining GPIand its own PCL printer command language for a future printer.andO;GMS Inc may be the first to announce a GPI compatible printer inApril 1989.andP;  Microsoft hopes to diminish the dominance of AdobeSystem's Postscript page description language by introducing adevice-specific driver that requires less memory.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   OS/2 Presentation Manager (Graphical user interface) (usage).andO;Topic:     PrintersPage Description LanguagesDevice DriversCompatible HardwareCompatible SoftwareGraphical User Interface.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Diane BernardandM;Microsoft Corp. is working with printer manufacturers and software developersto create a widespread printing environment for OS/2 Presentation Managergraphics, according to officials at the Redmond, Wash., company.andM;The efforts, ranging from the creation of high-end printers to thedevelopment of Presentation Manager device drivers for dot-matrix and low-endlaser printers (see related story below), hold promise for a new generationof fast, inexpensive printers, according to printer manufacturers andindustry observers.andM;Microsoft hopes printer companies will support Presentation Manager graphicsby implementing different levels of PM's graphical programming interface(GPI) code into their machines, said Adrian King, the company's director ofOS/2 product marketing.andP;  GPI, the source code at the heart of thePresentation Manager's graphics capabilities, will provide the mostsophisticated levels of PM support among printers.andM;Phoenix Technologies Ltd. is developing a printer, which could be announcedthis fall, that implements GPI as a printer language, said Bill Hilliard,product marketing manager at the Norwood, Mass., company.andP;  ''Microsoft isinterested in developing a printer architecture tuned to OS/2 printing, andin defining it as a standard,'' Hilliard said.andM;Hewlett-Packard Co. is also pursuing GPI printer development for the OS/2environment.andP;  ''Our work is headed toward weaving parts of PCL [HP's printercommand language] and GPI into a printer language that doesn't needtranslation between the printer and the screen,'' said Bill McGlynn,Hewlett-Packard marketing manager for the printer division in Boise, Idaho.andO;McGlynn declined to provide an expected release date for the product.andM;While Phoenix and Hewlett-Packard are still in the early product-developmentstages, industry sources expect QMS Inc. to be the first to announce aGPI-based printer next month.andM;GPI could pose a serious challenge to the grip Adobe Systems Inc. has on thehigh-end printer market with its PostScript page-description language,observers  said.andM;Because GPI printers will be device-specific for OS/2, printer makers will beable to use memory more efficiently than PostScript printers that mustsupport many different systems, observers said.andM;''High-end GPI printers will cost less than printers using PostScript becausePostScript is not device-specific,'' said Phoenix Technologies' Hilliard.andM;Liz Bond, marketing manager at Adobe, defended PostScript and added that thebenefits of GPI remain to be seen.andP;  ''PostScript exists on a variety ofprinting solutions because it's a device-independent solution,'' she said.andM;GPI printers will also run high-quality graphics much faster because the sameprinter language interfaces with the screen and drives the printer, said RobAuster, group director of electronic printing at market-research firm CAPInternational Inc. in Norwell, Mass.andM;A GPI-based language in printers will eliminate the need to translate thescreen language into the printer language, a time-consuming process that isrequired to print PostScript graphics, Auster said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>